## Goals

* Provide 12V power for sonar, clamp, fan, ethernet switch, Xavier and FPGA pcb
* Provide 5V power for torpedos and control pcb
* Provide 3.3V power for current sensor and control pcb
* Design kill switch for external component
* Monitor the current of each motor
* Open circuit if too strong current by fuse
* Provide 5V power for RGB LED strip
* Easy to connect

# <u>12V buck converter</u>

## **Application**

With 24.83A and 298W to deliver, we need a big buck with heatsink because we need to power the Xavier, the sonar, the two other buck, fan, ethernet switch and the FPGA Board. In other way, we have to power everything except the droppper, the LED, the motors and the pods LED.

# <u>5V buck converter</u>

## **Theory**

Datasheet


You can find all this detailed procedure in the datasheet of the buck controller LM3150

### **<u>First part</u>**

For this one, we will design a full buck converter external MOSFET **11A max on 5V output**.

This image represent a typical buck converter, but we are going to use a Synchronous Rectifier which means two MOSFET so we don't need a Schottky diode. We are going to use a DC/DC switching controllers the [LM3150MHX/NOPB](https://www.ti.com/lit/ds/symlink/lm3150.pdf?HQS=TI-null-null-digikeymode-df-pf-null-wwe&ts=1603127094356) and two MOSFET with N channel .

[![](attachments/39223327/39223348.png)](https://components101.com/articles/buck-converter-basics-working-design-and-operation)

Here is a basic buck converter, in our case, we will have a schematic more like this:

[![](https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Muhammad_Malik93/publication/283668013/figure/fig1/AS:415531980083201@1476081952980/Buck-Synchronous-Rectifier-Buck-Converters-a-Buck-Converter-b-Synchronous-Buck.png)](https://www.researchgate.net/figure/Buck-Synchronous-Rectifier-Buck-Converters-a-Buck-Converter-b-Synchronous-Buck_fig1_283668013)

To make the buck, we begin with the inductor size.

First of all you have to know the input voltage, the ouput voltage, the switching frequency and the output current of the buck.

1. Vin = 12V, Vout = 5V, DC = Vout/Vin ~42%. After that, you want a frequency which is possible to do for the controller, so we decided to have 500kHz, because we are limited by the controller specs and the Toff and the Ton minimum times. We can calculate the Fsmax by using this equation:

Fsmax = (Vout/Vin-max)/tON-MIN = (5/13)/200ns = 1.923MHz

But we should reduce the switching frequency and meet the following criteria :

Fs < (1 - Vout/Vin)/725ns = (1 - 5/12)/725ns = 800kHz

So we we need to select a frequency under 800kHz for the switching frequency of the device

2. Inductor L is found by this equation:

![](attachments/39223327/40697867.png)

With Vin=12V, Vout= 5V, Fsw = 500Khz (switching frequency of the two signal to drive the MOSFET). To determine the value, you need to check Iout 10.6A and the ripple current r which is a value between 0.2 to 0.5 typically and found by this equation, here we're using 0.35.

We finally have a 1.52uF. After this, we need to find a part that can be use in our system with some specific request which are: Amp rate of min 11A, at least equal to L

3. Ouput capacitor is determined by it's minimum value equation :

![](attachments/39223327/40697869.png)

In our case we got 185 uF so we decided to pick 2 100uF capacitor. Furthermore, we need to determine the best ESR value for the system. The ESR max is calculated by this :

![](attachments/39223327/40697870.png)

where Af = 1 because we are using a feed-forward capacitor, ET min =

![](attachments/39223327/40697875.png)

where Fs is in Khz. We get 5.65 V\*usec. So ESR max result 21.44 mΩ

After we need the ESR min and it must meet both of these equation:

![](attachments/39223327/40697876.png)

And ETmax is just ET min but with the Vin max value. We found out 3.79mΩ and 4.29mΩ, so we take the 3.97mΩ.

Ouput capacitor


So we need 2 capacitors of 100 uF, with an ESR between 3.97mΩ to 21.44mΩ so we took the 6SVPE220MW 2 times

Finally for the Mosfet, we need to calculate the Qg total max, the Vds and the power dissipation of the Mosfet.

1. ![](attachments/39223327/40697879.png)

Where IVCCL is the minimum current limit of VCC, over the temperature range specified in the datasheet of the controller, here its 65mA. So we can have a maximum of 130nC for the gate charge of the two MOSFET. The MOSFET gate charge Qg is gathered from reading the VGS vs Qg curve of the MOSFET datasheet at the VGS = 5 V for the high-side, M1, MOSFET and VGS = 6 V for the low-side, M2, MOSFET.

2. For the Vds, we simply use a mosfet with a maximum drain-source voltage greater than 1.2 x 12 V = 14.4V

3. Finally, We have to calculate the maximum power dissipation that the MOSFET need to handle but to do this, we need to pick one MOSFET to have its RDS(ON) resistance, or you can take the one that WeBench gives you in the simulation and confirm it's compatibility. the CSD16342Q5A has 11nC at maximum and the CSD17577Q5A poses at max 11nC too.

Finally, the RDS(ON) at 6.1mΩ for both so we can calculate :

![](attachments/39223327/40697883.png)

and by summing that, we are getting 0.317W, so it will be fine.

### **<u>Second part : features</u>**

After reading the datasheet of the controller, we decided that we need to use three features for the Buck :

* The soft start (Css)
* The current limit (Rlim)
* Duty cycle (Ron)

We also have to calculate Cin, Cff, Rrfb1 ands Rfb2. Let's begin with them.

1. The input capacitor should be chosen so that the voltage rating is greater than the maximum input voltage which for this example is 12.5 V. After, The input capacitor should also be able to handle the input rms current, which is a  
   maximum of approximately 0.5 x IOUT so 3.85A. Here's the equation:

![](attachments/39223327/40697887.png)

We got 6.5uF, so we decided to have two 10uF to accept more easily the input rms current and one aluminum electrolytic capacitors about 5 time greater to deal with any resonant circuit.

2\. Rfb1 and Rfb2 are a voltage divider to set the ouput voltage, here is 5V. Rfb1 is locked at a certain value 10kΩ, (for a low current and not create some noise) and after we solve this equation to get Rfb2:

![](attachments/39223327/40697890.png)

so we get 73.33kΩ. We need to be as close as possible to this value.

3\. Cff is a feed-forward ceramic capacitor, and we can find its value by this equation:

![](attachments/39223327/40697889.png)

We finally get 98.55pF so a 100pF is perfect for our build.

4.Now let's find the parts for the features. First let's attack the soft-start. The SS is important to prevent any over current at the startup caused by the load such as empty capacitors. We need at beginning to check the minimum soft start time. The soft-start time should be greater than the input voltage rise time and also satisfy the following equality to maintain a smooth transition of the output voltage to the programmed regulation voltage during start-up.

![](attachments/39223327/40697892.png)

so we got at minimum 3.33msec. So if we want a 5msec we are going to use this equation:

![](attachments/39223327/40697893.png)

So we get a 68 nF ceramic capacitor rate at more than 10V and a 5% range.

5\. For the current limit, we need to find a resistance value to place on the ILIM pin of the controller. We need to find the Mosfet before doing this section to have the Rds(on) value of the MOSFET.

![](attachments/39223327/40697894.png)

So we select an current variation in the inductor of about 30% of 11 Iout and a Iocl of 10.6A. We finally arrive at 1021Ω, so we took an 1.02kΩ res.

6\. Finally we want a resistance To control the duty cycle of the signal to the MOSFET. We find it by this equation :

![](attachments/39223327/40697895.png)

We got 100kΩ but in WeBench got 82.5kΩ, so we pick something in the middle 88.7kΩ.

# <u>3.3V buck converter</u>

### Theory

For this one, we need something who deliver 0.31A and use 1.02W. With this very low demands of power, we can use a simple LDO (Low-Dropout regulator). A**LDO**regulator is a DC[linear voltage regulator](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regulator "Linear regulator")that can regulate the outputvoltageeven when the supply voltage is very close to the output voltage. The advantages of the LDO are first, simple to understand with not many parts, affordable. On the other hand, to make the dropout voltage, an linear DC/DC regulator must dissipate the power. The power is the potential difference between the voltage in and the voltage out of the regulator. So it's way we are going to connect it from the lowest voltage available to reduce the power dissipated.

# <u>Loadswitch circuit</u>

## **Theory**

Having some loadswitch is the easiest way to control a supply without damaging the electronics with the current flow. We will be using the TPS22810DBVR. This chip in a SOT23-5 package can handle 2 amp which is more than we can give. After, it has a wide input range 2.7V to 18V for supply, so we can use it for both 12V fan and the 3.3V devices. It have three features for our case: The QOD, a rise time capacitor to prevent an inrush current, an thermal shutdown for security and finally an enable input with logic state.

First we need to find a fan with a 50x50mm size and use less than 2 A to run to ensure our chip selection.

||||
<colgroup><col /><col /><col /></colgroup>|---|---|---|
|#|Title|Notes|
|1|[AB5015H12](https://www.amazon.ca/Security-01-Bearing-Brushless-Cooling-AB5020H12/dp/B01N9ZQRI7)|<ul title=""><li>Big 50x50mm fan</li><li>Most important information given</li><li>188.7 CFM</li><li>0.15A</li></ul>|
|2|[F310R-12LLC](https://www.digikey.com/en/products/detail/nidec-copal-electronics/F310R-12LLC/1165521)|<ul><li>small 30x30mm fan</li><li>Good datasheet</li><li>Only 2.1 CFM</li><li>0.04A</li></ul>|
|3|[HA40101V4-1000U-A99](https://www.digikey.com/en/products/detail/sunon-fans/HA40101V4-1000U-A99/6198728)|<ul><li>40x40mm fan</li><li>Very poor information on the Datasheet or in chinese shit</li><li>0.031A </li></ul>|

So we select The AB5015H12 brushless fan since it has what we need.

Now we can design our circuit.

![](attachments/39223327/41517103.png)

1. **<u>Firs step:</u>** What is the capacitor load
   1. For the fan, we don't have any capacitive load known so we put an 10uF ceramic to realize our calculation.
   2. For the I2C, We have 25uF of capacitive load.
2. **<u>Second step:</u>**Rext
   1. To calculate Rext, we need:
      * Vin/Vout value
      * The desired fall time, here 20ms is sufficient
      * The approximate Rpd value, depending of the supply value
      * The capacitor load value
   2. using this equation :
      1. ![](attachments/39223327/41517102.png)

         ![](attachments/39223327/41517104.png)

         Keep in mind that Vcap is about 10% of Vout and Vin 90% of Vout because the fall time is mesured from the 90 to 10% of Vout. So for 12V, we obtained 910Ω and 364Ω too for the 3.3V.
   3. With Rqod, we can find Rext with this equation:

![](attachments/39223327/41517106.png)

And find Rpd depending of the Vin in this graph

![](attachments/39223327/41517105.png)

So for the 12V loadswitch we got Rpd = 250Ω and for the 3.3V it's about 275Ω.

We finally end with a 660Ω value with for the 12Vfan and 90Ω for the 3.3V devices, so we just don't put any resistor between Rqod and Vout since the 3.3V should create a 12mA inside the Rpd.

1. **<u>Third step:</u>** CT
   1. For the fan, since we have about 10uF, we want a maximum of 200mA inrush current. So we can calculate the approximative rise time needed for this inrush :

      ![](attachments/39223327/41517202.png)

      so we get 480usec for the Fan with I=200mA, Cl=10uF, Vout = 9.6V(80% of Vin). We can choose in the table a CT value who gives a bigger rise time than 480usec.
   2. For the 3.3 I2C device, we have around 25uF, we want an maximum of 400mA inrush current. So we can calculate the approximative rise time needed for this inrush with the upper equation

Since we have a Vout of about 2.64V, we have a rise time of 165usec. Let's go check the table :

We can now choose 27000pF for the Fan and for the 3.3V I2C too because we have a bigger rise time in both design.

1. ## **Find E, the energy that is converted into heat during the demagnetization of the inductive loads**

## ![](attachments/39223327/42139650.png)

   1. ### <u>First we need the ouput current and the inductor</u>

Before anything else, we can use this equation because we approximate the resistive load at 0. So after a fast check at the power architecture, we are powering the 8 motors, the 2 LED strip and the gripper.

We conclude that we can reach about 106 A since one motor can reach 25 A and a max of 4 can works simultaneously, no gripper can works at the same time of the 4 motors, but the LED can.

For the Inductor, we assume the gripper and the LED have no inductor value. For the motor, we have a 0.07mH for one phase of one motor. By doing some parallel coil equation we finally got 5.83 uH.

So we get E= 67.18mJ which is very fine in our case.

# <u>Connectors protections</u>

This section is very important for the securities of our systems. Indeed, we want to prevent any spark during our connection, because we can be, as human, charged and we don't want to discharge our body inside the circuit. To reduce this event to appear, we put specific Bipolar TVS diode. TVS AKA Transient-Voltage-Suppression is mainly used for protection of voltage spike. We want to protect the system from a brief over-voltage from the power source. To do so, we have to take the good TVS diode depending of the supply where we want the protection. The TVS diodes is defined by three specs:

* The maximum reverse voltage
* The breakdown voltage
* The clamping voltage(where the current is at it peaks)

Since we have four differents supply, we will have four differents diode, because the specs just can't be the same.

For the 3.3V supplied connections, we need a diode with a reverse voltage at maximum 3.3V, so we chose the [TVS3V3L4UE6327HTSA1](https://www.infineon.com/dgdl/TVS3V3L4U_rev_2_2.pdf?folderId=db3a30431f848401011fcbf2ab4c04c4&fileId=db3a3043382e837301385be7912532ed),

for the 5V supplied connections, we need a diode with a reverse voltage at maximum 5V, so we chose the [SMBJ5.0A](https://www.bourns.com/docs/Product-Datasheets/SMBJ.pdf),

for the 12V supplied connections, we need a diode with a reverse voltage at maximum 12V, so we chose the [SMAJ12CA-13-F](https://www.vishay.com/docs/87606/smbj5cdthrusmbj120cd.pdf)

and finally, for the 18V supplied(battery voltage) connections, we need a diode with a reverse voltage at maximum 20V, so we chose the [SMBJ20CA-E3/52](https://www.vishay.com/docs/87606/smbj5cdthrusmbj120cd.pdf),
